            Euophryini Simon, 1901
is the largest tribe of jumping spiders, with more than 1000 described species (around 15% of the salticid species described) distributed in various terrestrial ecosystems around the world (

; 

). 

contributed to delimiting the group, based mainly on the embolus form. 

, based on phylogenetic analyses using molecular data, compiled a list with 34 genera. Later, 

, also using molecular data, showed that many lineages with different embolus also belonged in the group (including 

Soesilarishius
Makhan, 2007

and 

Popcornella
Zhang & Maddison, 2012

), increasing the number of genera up to 85. A more recent phylogenetic study (

) combined molecular and morphological data, and increased the genus list of the tribe up to 108 genera (including 

Rhyphelia
Simon, 1902

, based on similarities with 

Soesilarishius

). The tribe currently includes more than 130 genera (

).

Photographs of fixed specimens were taken using a Leica DFC420 digital camera connected to an M205A stereomicroscope. Male palps were dissected and illustrated in alcohol in different positions to indicate the structures under a stereomicroscope with a camera lucida. For the internal structure of the female epigynes, they were dissected, immersed in clove oil (

), and illustrated under a microscope with a camera lucida. Scanning electron micrographs (SEM) were taken with Mira3 Tescan or Zeiss Leo 1450 VP (Laboratório Institucional de Microscopia Eletrônica de Varredura of the Museu Paraense Emílio Goeldi), after critical point. The measurements are expressed in millimeters. Annotations concerning macrosetae are restricted to development of ventral spines of tibiae I, given the uniformity of the remaining spines across the lineage (

, 

; 

).

The following abbreviations are used throughout the descriptions: A: apophysis; E: embolus; 

BG
: Bennett’s gland

; 

PA
: paraembolic apophysis; S1: primary spermatheca; S2: secondary spermatheca

; 

RTA
: retrolateral tibial apophysis (vRTA: ventral branch of 
RTA
; dRTA: dorsal branch of 
RTA

).

